<TITLE> Philippine transport groups call strike over fuel costs </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MANILA, Dec 12 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Philippine transport groups have called for a nationwide strike on Thursday to protest against the high cost of oil and demand the government removes a 12 percent tax on fuel sales. "Instead of going to the office or school, just go to the strike and rally centres and join our fight against the unjustifiable oil price hikes," George San Mateo, leader of a left-wing transport group PISTON, said in a statement. There has not been a countrywide transport strike in the Philippines since the early 1980s, when former dictator Ferdinand Marcos was still in power, but recent leaps in the price of oil have stoked anger among taxi drivers and bus operators. Commuter buses, mini-buses, taxis and other forms of public transport are expected to stop plying their routes in key urban centres such as Manila, Cebu, Baguio, Davao and Iloilo cities on Thursday. Leftist groups also called on workers and students to take to the streets and help paralyse Manila, hoping to force lawmakers to review a law deregulating the oil industry and remove a 12 percent sales tax on fuel products. "It is a small sacrifice, a minor inconvenience," said Renato Reyes, secretary-general of Bayan, an umbrella group of leftist organisations, as he called on the people to support the nationwide transport strike. "If there is a chance for us to generate a strong protest to stop another oil price increase, then it is well worth the one-day inconvenience." National police chief Avelino Razon said security forces in the capital will go on alert on Wednesday night to guard a large oil depot. Razon said police trucks would be on standby to ferry commuters shut out from their usual mode of transport. The government expects economic growth this year to hit 7 percent, the highest rate in more than 30 years, but the higher price of oil has hiked electricity bills and fuel costs. The prohibitive price of power has cut the amount of Christmas lights festooned around the archipela